<h3>Comments</h3>

<p>I read your question a few days ago, and then I read Jeanne's
reply, and I kind of agree with Jeanne that Confucius probably
did not want exclude women from his &quot;theory&quot;. Also when
he says &quot;man&quot;,I think he means human being not
nessecery female or male. In many other languages we do not have
to say &quot;man&quot;and than&quot;women&quot; for all sexes to
be considered. When it goes to women philosophers, there are a
big amount of women philosophers, sometimes they call themselves
feminists in France for example, but their feminism differs alot
from American feminists. They call themselves feminists because
they are extremley well educated, especially in philosophy.</p>
